<DOC><DOCNO> AP891124-0168 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-89 2338EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-Vietnamese     11-24 0270</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Vietnamese,0278</SECOND><HEAD>Rival Vietnamese Groups Battle in Refugee Camp</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Several hundred stone-throwing Vietnameserefugees fought a pitched battle inside a detention center Saturdayand police fired more than 20 rounds of tear gas grenades to regaincontrol, officials reported.   Police said the fighting at the Shek Kong center involved rivalgroups from different provinces in Vietnam and began after one manwas attacked.   They reported three Vietnamese were hospitalized for injuriesand one police officer was wounded slightly.   There have been frequent fights in recent months amongVietnamese boat people held in detention camps in this smallBritish colony.   More than 55,000 Vietnamese refugees are languishing in the HongKong camps, hoping for resettlement and fearing repatriation totheir communist-ruled homeland.   It is expected that tens of thousands of boat people will bedenied refugee status by Hong Kong, and tension has increased inthe camps with the possibility that they will be sent back toVietnam.   The United Nations Refugee Agency asked the Hong Kong governmentFriday to investigate allegations that undue force was used whenmoving Vietnamese refugees from one camp to another.   The Hong Kong office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugeeshad earlier protested the circumstances of an early morningtransfer on Oct. 31 of 48 Vietnamese.   Some of the Vietnamese told the U.N. agency that security forcesused martial-arts tactics to immobilize them during the move from adetention center to a holding center for refugees who may beforcibly sent back to Vietnam.   The government denied earlier this week that unreasonable forcewas used during the transfer.</TEXT></DOC>